Text: Hello, how am I, I am OK, thanks. How old am I, I am in my mid 20s. My name is Sarah Williams.

What does bring me along (here) today, I have come for an eye examination (here) today because I am having some problems with double vision. I have come for an eye test today because I am getting double vision again. The double vision is really bothering me and I can't make it back into one image whereas before I could. I only get the double vision when I am reading in the evenings. I love reading and do it most nights, but this is when I notice the double vision. I get the double vision when reading at night quite frequently, particularly if I am tired. This time, I first noticed it about one month ago. The double vision is not getting worse, the only thing that makes it go away is if I look into the distance. When I get the double vision I often get headaches too, quite bad ones and I often have to take paracetamol. The headaches are at the top front middle of my head to start with and then they move down to the back of my head, like a mohawk I would describe it as. The headaches started around the same time as the double vision, about one month ago, although I used to get some headaches before that. I can get headaches every evening when I am reading. I think all the studying I am doing at the moment is contributing to the double vision and headaches.

My last sight was very recently actually, about 3 months ago. I got some new distance glasses at my last sight test about 3 months ago. I also got contact lenses then, 3 months ago so, I could get back to playing netball, which is great fun. I have been getting these problems with headaches and double vision so I thought I would come in sooner than when I was due, I hope that this is alright.
I don't get any flashing lights or floaters in my vision.
I wear my glasses all the time. I need my glasses for my distance vision, I could not see anything properly without them.

I wear my contact lenses mostly for sporty things. I wear my contact lens about 4 hours per day but only wear them 3 days per week, I would say. Sometimes I might wear my contact lenses more often but overall probably about 3 days per week.

I do have quite a complicated history with my eyes, it all started when I was very young, and I had two surgeries on my eyes. I think they put Botox in before too, I found that really funny like what they use for face lifts in my eyes! Who would have thought! I have my notes from the surgery here, sorry I can't remember what I had done without this, but it is 6mm off the Left Medial rectus and they moved the position of the Lateral rectus. I also had to wear a cover or patch over my eyes for a couple of years when I was a child. I also had some triangle prism things put into my glasses too. I don't have any other problems though, never had any pain or had to have any medications, and I was discharged from the hospital when I turned 10. I haven't had any other eye problems, just the turn in my eye and surgery when I was a kid.

My family also have health conditions, my grandparents have heart disease and high blood pressure. No one in my family has arthritis or diabetes. I am very glad about this because I couldn't think of anything worse than arthritis.

There are some eye problems in my family, for example my brother does have a little squint, but nothing like mine used to be and his glasses correct it, he never had to have any of the patches or anything. In all the family photos when we were little, I was the only pirate!

The only medication I take is antihistamines for my hay fever. I think that pollen seems to be affecting me less and less, so there is a positive, I don't take the antihistamines as often as I used to.
My general health is very good, I couldn't tell you the last time I went to the GP, I never seem to get ill so I don't have any reason to go really.

I do like to read a lot, but I am really struggling recently, especially when I am reading in bed before I go to sleep, I used to be able to see just one image but now I see two next to each other and even when I try, I just can't see clearly. It is really frustrating when I want to read but it is just too uncomfortable.

I work as a trainee solicitor at the moment, this is my living, job. To get promoted at work, I am in the processing of trying to sit my Bar exams, so I am doing a lot of revising and reading for work too. This does mean that I am on the computer a lot too though, around 10 hours every day. I also spend a couple of hours on social media on my phone.

My main hobby is playing netball, which I love so, I train twice a week and play a match once a week too. I hadn't played netball since primary school, but started a couple of months ago after I got contact lenses and I never thought I would enjoy it as much as I have been. It helps I can drive myself to practice netball now I've passed my test too, so I can go to as many netball training sessions as I want without relying on lifts from other people. I also enjoy reading. Reading is one of my favourite things to do (hobby), and I do a lot of it, both at work and in my spare time at home.
I drive. I don't smoke. For a living I work as a trainee solicitor.
I have nothing more to add. I have nothing else to tell you.
